{"key":"processedPost-9722513","value":{"id":9722513,"first":9706568,"last":9729832,"when":1233604820,"utime":"02/02/09 10:00 PM","cleanedPost":"If you search back over the years, you'll see every time we've tried to give good advice on lighting, some moron would come in to say \"if you can see your mushrooms, you have enough light\" and trash the thread.&nbsp; I'm surprised nobody has come in with that nonsense yet.<br />Evaporation of moisture from the substrate is probably the number 1 pinning trigger, because that gets everything started, thus you could also say fresh air exchange(FAE) is the number 1 pinning trigger, because without FAE, there is no evaporation, thus no pinning, or poor pinning.<br />Upper 90% humidity is required or the substrate dries out too much, and primordia formation is inhibited.&nbsp; Once these conditions have been met, light becomes a major pinning trigger.&nbsp; This is why we refer to light as a secondary pinning trigger.&nbsp; It doesn't mean it's less important, but it means that other conditions must be met first.<br />Of course, first and foremost is full colonization, and once that is accomplished and the mycelium has consolidated its hold on the substrate, you want to introduce the pinning triggers of FAE, high humidity, and light.<br />RR"}}